Design Principles — What Makes It Special
1. No Grinding Mentality
Starlight Deck is not a clicker game. There's no 'optimal strategy' to farm Careons endlessly. The
experience is designed to be savored, not conquered. If you find yourself grinding, you've missed
the point.
2. Aesthetic Intention
Every visual choice matters. The gradient backgrounds, the glowing progress bars, the card borders
— these aren't decorations. They're environmental cues that signal: 'slow down, you're in a sacred
space.'
3. Gentle Gamification
Yes, there are Careons and VIP badges. But these aren't high-pressure metrics. They're soft
nudges to stay engaged. The real reward is the reflection itself, not the points.
4. Community Without Competition
No leaderboards. No public rankings. No 'top players.' The SLD Network Fund rises together, and
everyone benefits equally when milestones are reached. This is cooperation over conquest.
5. Mysticism Meets Transparency
The cards feel magical, but the code is open. The AI feels wise, but it's clearly labeled as AI (Gemini).
This balance of enchantment and honesty is crucial — we're not pretending to be fortune tellers.
The Charm Checklist ■
When adding features or refactoring code, ask yourself these questions to ensure you're preserving
the original magic:
✓ Does this feature encourage slowing down or speeding up?
✓ Does it foster reflection or mindless clicking?
✓ Does it feel communal or isolating?
✓ Is the visual design beautiful and intentional?
✓ Does it respect the user's time and attention?
✓ Would Estrella approve of this feature's tone?
✓ Does it add depth or just complexity?
✓ Can someone use this feature mindfully?
✓ Does it align with the cosmic cozy aesthetic?
✓ Is there a way to make this simpler without losing meaning?
If a feature fails more than 3 of these checks, reconsider it.
Preserving the Essence During Technical Work
As you refactor code, add databases, fix bugs, and scale the app, it's easy to lose sight of the soul of
Starlight Deck. Here are concrete ways to keep the charm alive:
When Refactoring
• Keep function names evocative: `draw_cosmic_card()` beats `get_random_item()`
• Preserve comments that explain why, not just what
• Don't optimize away the 'pauses' — loading states can be meditative
• Test the feel, not just the functionality
When Adding Features
• Start with mockups to ensure visual consistency
• Write the copy first — does it sound like Starlight Deck?
• Ask: 'Does this add depth or distraction?'
• Test with users who've never seen the app — do they feel the vibe?
When Debugging
• Fix the bug, but don't strip the magic
• Error messages should still feel on-brand (e.g., 'The cosmos is confused. Try again?')
• If you add console logs, make them poetic: `console.log('■ Card drawn at twilight')`
